The tenant of Bakal: The poolets are warming, he signed a higher rent.
An imposing old man came out by the door of the customer center of the company RPG Byty of the "baron of coal" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
He was carrying a file with three new leases for three apartments: his own, his daughter’s, and his son’s, who is serving a sentence.
The deregulation has increased rent for these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay from next year for an apartment 2<0x2B>1 second category 4100 crowns.
"And there is no hot water and the heating works on solid fuel," the man who has the power to sign shows with the finger on his son's new contract.
"But I signed anyway," he explains in anger and half resigned.
The citizen association of apartments BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and wait until December 7, when a notice will be published to explain the method to be followed to claim.
But man reacts to this by a hand gesture.
"One says this, the other says something else," frowning his eyebrows.
The Ostrava region becomes the laboratory of deregulation.
After the New Year, this is what most apartments in the Czech Republic expect, the rents of which do not correspond to the market price.
Aktualne.cz has therefore decided to visit the "laboratory" personally.
The RPG waiting room in Havirovska street is one of four in the Ostrava region and it is already full on Tuesday at 9 a.m.
Right next to the door stands a security guard with a device to call customers.
A special button, "lease 2011", is lit on the touch screen.
One print and one paper with a number comes out of the device.
You don't have time to read your number "157" as your number already starts to light up on the big screen under the hood of the waiting room.
In a fraction of a second, it's your turn.
After a short moment, an old couple arrives to inquire about the rent, but the new rents do not seem to concern people in the waiting room.
The majority of people have come to solve common problems like everywhere - demand for repairs, insurance events, and more.
In the Ostrava region, people from more than 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio have been picking up mail with new leases in their mailbox since around mid-November.
RPG Byty offers them rent increases of 15 to 38 percent.
The special shop for new rentals has been open to the public since 18 November.
"it's been running for almost a week, so it's still on trial" answers, after a moment of hesitation, the employee behind the counter when the client presents himself as a journalist.
The deragulation and the former minor apartments of Bakal are a very sensitive local subject.
The vice-president of the parliament and native of the region of Ostrava Lubomir Zaoralek of the Social Democrats made a fairly supportive statement before the elections and this now fills the local newspapers.
"Twenty years after them, I want a new floor."
"They didn't even change a put...n board in the toilets, relieves in introduction the man mentioned.
However, it is mostly, according to employees, retirees who come to be sure that they will receive a refund on the new rental price if they now sign as promised by RPG in a special offer.
This is a refund of half the amount of the rent that will be received by the other tenants who will have signed their new contract before December 15.
But the "deregulation" counter of Havirovaska street is really not overwhelmed by questions.
“Among the 360 customers who came yesterday, only 40 to 50 came to rent it,” the employee said.
And yet RPG promotes both on its website and in the showcases of individual rental interviews when needed.
If both parties do not agree on the rent, it is an independent court that will make the decision.
“It’s not about threats, it’s just about informing about the unique and legitimate way to act legally,” RPG said on its website.
"Nobody's going to court here," thinks one of Byty's RPG employees, and the man in the street in front of the customer center gives him reason.
“I have 13,000 crowns and I have 5,000 crowns left to eat, I don’t have enough to go to court,” he said.
The employee suddenly feels uneasy.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaoralek in the media asks that no one sign and therefore people wait," she said.
Rent regulation ends in the Czech Republic at the beginning of 2011 and increases, according to RPG Byty, are an economic necessity.
"And, moreover, the current rents still do not reach the necessary level for the simple maintenance of the housing fund," recalls Pavel Klimes, director of the residential portfolio of RPG Byty, that it is precisely the negligence of the housing fund that makes the tenant angry.
However, in 5 years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest with rents in 4 billion apartments, in four years from 2011 to 2014 this is expected to be 5.2 billion.
The large screen hung on the ceiling in front of the upholstered armchairs in the waiting room of Havirosvka Street, however, repeats some information indicated in red.
“The rent increase in 2011 is 15 percent and concerns no less than 31,200 apartments, or more than 90 percent of RPG apartments.”
"And it will always be a maximum of 7.50 Czech crowns per m2 per month," the screen says.
The 38 percent increase concerns only 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
"In these cases, this is an increase of a really very low amount of CZK 19.66 per m2," adds RPG.
Next year the rent will remain the same for 2600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not cause a radical but gradual increase over 4 to 8 years.
It adds other commitments: all the money from the increase in rents (see the graph) is returned to the apartments in the form of heating savings - new windows and heating.
Those who sign the agreement on the increase in rent have priority.
The kindergarten is also part of the offices that included the architects.
the administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch. Design.
No one could have expected that it would also house a mini kindergarten with everything needed - colored walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch. design employees can go there.
The architectural-project company Arch. Design. whose workshops have produced a large number of constructions in Brno, has imagined its mini-business school since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
She employs about 90 people, mostly of childbearing age, and she cared that women architects and project managers could quickly get back to work.
At the same time as reduced-time employment contracts, the kindergarten is a bonus offered to its employees by the company Arch. Design. as part of its social program.
Builders and architects thus have the opportunity to combine a work that takes care of children.
It was the employees of Arch.Design. themselves who conceived this kindergarten and with the support of the management they were able to obtain a qualification from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini kindergarten is financed by the European Social Fund through the Operational Human Resources Programme and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
They were able to purchase equipment and equipment and after two years they were able to provide qualified staff and get started thanks to funding grants (up to CZK 2.8 million).
After the use of the funding endowment (two years) the company Arch. Design. has the obligation after 3 years to run the mini kindergarten on its own funds.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and it was the Economy rating company that helped to make the application for endowment.
Children's care is provided by qualified staff, a nurse and a kindergarten teacher take care of the children throughout the day. children can go to kindergarten without age limitation but they have more than three years for most.
As it is a "mini kindergarten" there can be only 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there are more who replace themselves.
The functioning of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use this school regardless of the hierarchical position.
Although it is an individual care and education, the mini kindergarten program is comparable to the one for preschool education.
Children do not just play there, but quality teaching is also ensured - from the beginning to the preparation to the school benches, English is taught.
The class is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can control their child at any time and not have the stress of a delay in going to pick up the children in a school away from the parent’s workplace.
Parents use their working time in the most productive way.
It is not surprising that there is a natural relationship of loyalty between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design.s is thus registered among companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and are family-friendly and through this program strengthens HR marketing.
The bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look at Gaudi’s interiors.
The toe resembles the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase to a dinosaur spine, and the balconies to open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by the architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic forms, the house received the nickname Maison en bon from the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present of curves, this is all that is typical for Art Nouveau by Antoni Gaudi.
The front facade of the house unfolds its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
In the course of a more detailed observation we see the geometry, the rhythm and the order thought accurately.
At night the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brilliance of colors is reinforced.
The winding and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood in waves copies the window frames, balustrades, decorative elements of the doors, the eyeliner and the slats.
The Battlo house that stands in the Eixample district in the shopping street Passeig de Gracia at number 43, was born from the construction of an 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, first insisted on the demolition of the old construction and the construction of another all-new but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-apartment house was not thought by Gaudi alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was precisely on his project that the decorations for an apartment representing the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade were born.
For the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade also worked other artists and creators.
The joint work on the plans of Casa Battlo began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi's Casa Mila house and Guell Park in which there are other works of Gaudi.
The locals nicknamed the house hot just after its finish because of its organic shapes "the House in Bone".
Others, in view of the specific mechanism of opening the windows, called it "the down house".
It is said that at the top of the construction there is a sword similar to that of Saint George the patron of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the construction contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with typical ventilation vents and chimneys.
Their 45-degree inclination seems odd.
During the creation Gaudi absolutely did not comply with the construction guidelines of then and did not let himself be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained from the city the permit to build, knowing, of course, that the data carried on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the completion the municipal council was horrified and demanded modifications.
It did not please, for example, the members of the municipal council that the pillars of the construction are imbedded on the public sidewalk.
There was never a change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city Josep Battlo requested (and obtained satisfaction) permission to rent the two higher floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and on the third one a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewellery store.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which one accesses to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The common part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit itself to private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi received in addition to new facades a non-traditional toy and two additional floors.
Gaudi’s play with light is also impressive, blue and white glass tiles with which the interior courtyard is decorated and with light wells.
The two-color game gives maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply enough to bet on the principle that white reflects more than the dark which, on the contrary, absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house that was registered in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and the most beautiful apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued the visits because they found it to be a lucrative enterprise and they expanded the field of visits to the common areas and the attic including the terraces of toi.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really inexpensive and costs 16.50 euros; students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entry price in Gaudi's other buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you must quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
