Devices to track people are increasingly in demand by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child is causing more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars, can also be used to trace the movement of people and help in some cases such as that of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a box of lights but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka has touched a large number of people and they have started looking for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
“We’re trying to tell everyone that this is not a spy but just another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy,” said Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the leading providers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is not aware, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
“The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons,” adds Pilin.
According to him, children should always know for what purposes "the box" is used and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention that if the child does not want to wear something like this on him, he will get rid of it.
“And even the smallest can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something when they don’t want to be under control.”
“Mobile phones, which can cut off like these tracking devices, have already brought parents to long expectations,” says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is very questionable.
“If it’s a pre-prepared kidnapping, the author will do everything to make sure the child doesn’t have an electronic device that can locate it.”
“Currently, it’s the phone.”
“As soon as the tracking devices are developed, they will be looking for them as well because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign.”
“In such cases, criminals will always be ahead of the police,” the psychologist said.
She admits, however, that such devices can help with an assault unprepared by a paedophile.
According to Robert Cech of the company RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, says having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an attack.
"The device can be set in such a way that it is in regular emission after a certain period of time."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, it remains the last position of the person concerned."
“The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who slipped and is in the elongated position without moving,” says Cech.
According to him, so-called smartphones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after formatting it with a special prologue.
The problem with current tracking systems is that it is either a device similar to those worn in pendant the size of a lighter box or to the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of the company Macro Weil, that is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential attacker will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he'll realize it after a while, which will have given the police a little more time," he added.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as for car tracking.
It is a combination of position acquisition systems using GPS (which is commonly used in self-navigation) and a function of a mobile phone that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
