An index longer than the annular one is a sign of a low risk of cancer
Men who have the index longer than the annular are exposed to a lower risk of having prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This can depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, especially for men before the age of 60," said co-author of the study Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
The finger could thus help determine which men should undergo prostate cancer test, particularly by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, said Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009 she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had a shorter right-hand index than the annual one.
For them, as for 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the annular, however, the risk dropped to 33 percent, for men before 60 the risk reduction reached 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two fingers cited - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it is testosterone that helps in the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of this study but does not appear to him that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
