Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries around the Pacific of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has gone from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It has also increased in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a sharp decline in production last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Table 2).
Some 44% of respondents in the region said they were satisfied with the way their country's democracy worked in practice; this was the same figure as last year, but with a sharp increase from 25% in 2001 (Chart 3)
Some 34% said they had confidence in the Parliament of their country and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but a strong increase compared to 2003 (respectively 17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, the economic problems in Latin America shook the support for democracy.
If this has held up well during the global financial crisis, it is certainly due to the fact that many countries in America suffered only a brief recession and benefited from a strong recovery.
In addition, a social security network has helped protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and fell again this year, to 32%.)
But the mood varies considerably from country to country (see graph 4).
Brazil’s good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz In<0xC3><0xA1>cio Lula da Silva, translates into a widely shared sense of progress
This is rarer in Mexico and Central America where the recession has been more severe and violent crimes have worsened.
It is only the second time since the survey began that more respondents across Latin America as a whole have cited crime rather than unemployment as the most important problem for their country (see Table 5).
Approximately 31% say that they or a loved one of them have been the victim of a crime in the past year; however, this figure is down from 38% last year and is the lowest since 1995.
A more robust economic performance is reflected in the rise in support for private enterprise and the market economy: about 71% of respondents in the region say that private enterprise is essential for development, compared with 56% in 2007 (see Figure 6).
Some 58% believe that the market economy is the only system that will make their country developed, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela are of this opinion (and 80% support private enterprise); although their left-leaning president, Hugo Chavez, expropriates many private companies.
Brazil is the largest leader in the region, mentioned by 19% of respondents (against 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, down from 11% last year)
