The tip of the feet towards the center
The weeks after she suddenly became a widow, Cristina Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez, president of Argentina, benefited from a wave of public sympathy that improved her approval rate by 20 points, to more than 50%; this is her highest level since she was elected in 2007.
Yet, turning this into a successful campaign for a second term in an election next year might depend on Ms. Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez’s choice, apparently in mourning, whether or not she would abandon the intransigence of her late husband, predecessor and former political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, in this regard, the signs remain confused.
Mr. Kirchner, who continued to run economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, had a habit of drawing up budgets that underestimated tax revenue, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the first couple to spend additional income at will.
Ms. Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez’s government lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
