The economy is overheating widely: it is likely to grow by almost 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is now at 11.1%, but many private estimates and union wage claims see this figure close to 30%.
Mr. Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina feared an economic collapse, made growth and poverty reduction a priority, rather than controlling inflation.
He refused to deal with the IMF, he harassed the private sector and purged INDEC, the statistical office, which carried out falsifications of official inflation statistics.
Can Mrs. Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez now moderate these policies?
She called for talks between private companies and trade union leaders.
And his officials say they want to limit wage increases next year to 18%.
The economy has been stimulated by high global prices of Argentina's agricultural exports.
