Now Ms. Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez seems to be edging towards an agreement with creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which it owes some $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners have always insisted that this could not involve monitoring by the IMF, as is customary.
But last month, Amado Boudou, the Minister of Economy, announced that the Fund would provide "technical assistance" to design a new national consumer price index; which resembles a prelude to the sanitation of the INDEC.
It is not clear if Ms. Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez wants to remain in politics beyond the end of her term, now that her husband is no longer with her.
If she does, she needs to gain the support of the middle class, among which kirchnerism is highly proponent.
When the Argentines return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have refluxed.
If she wants to win another election, she will have to decide whether to reject, without noise, many of her husband’s policies.
