The Temecula Mosque project has been approved by the Planning Commission.
A mosque project in Temecula received unanimous support from the local planning commission after more than five hours of public testimony, often passionate.
Critics took up the project by claiming that it was promoting both terrorism and traffic congestion.
But the commissioners ruled Wednesday night that the new religious center respected local laws and would be aesthetically impressive.
“A lot of people have come to support it: Christians, Jews, Baha’is, you mention it,” Hadi Nael, president of the Islamic Centre of Temecula Valley, said Thursday morning.
"I am proud of it, as an American citizen."
"It shows that justice wins it."
“The opposition is really minimal,” he added.
“They just have very loud voices.”
"We have good people in this valley."
The session began at 6 p.m. and lasted until almost midnight with, most of the time, people pronouncing for or against the center, at roughly equally distributed speaking time, according to the Press-Enterprise.
The debate continued on the newspaper’s website.
“There is no longer America,” wrote one speaker.
"This is another planet of monkeys with Miss Liberty dead in the sand."
"America has fallen."
Planned Islamic centres also sparked protests in other parts of the country, including at Ground Zero, the site of the September 11, 2001 attacks in New York City.
Imam Mahmoud Harmoush has denounced violence in the Temecula Valley.
Her congregation of about 135 families co-existed without incident in Riverside County for years but she wanted a larger and better space than the warehouse she rented on a shared property with a water filtration system manufacturer.
The new 24,943-square-foot mosque in Mediterranean-style architecture would consist of two minarets and would rise to 43 feet high.
It would occupy a 4.32-hectare site on the Nicolas road about two miles east of Chaparral High School.
Opponents can still appeal against this project to the municipal council.
An arsenic-tolerant microbe raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, widens the field to find new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacterium here on Earth, they say it shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity."
"It can develop either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"That's why it's very particular, even if it's far from being a really "foreign" form of life," commented Paul Davies C. W. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report featured in Thursday's online edition of the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But researchers have found that the bacterium, discovered in Lake Mono, California, is able to continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
“We wonder what’s still possible,” said Ariel Anbar D. of the State University of Arizona, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, says Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not disclose the details of the finding, has generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could disclose the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
That was not the case.
The discovery "shows that, in other planetary environments, organisms may be able to use other elements to actuate biochemistry and that the "standard" set of elements, which we consider absolutely necessary for life, may not be fixed," said Charles Cockell, Scythian Professor at the Opentiut.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
“This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element to another in fundamental biochemistry and biochemical structure,” Cockell added.
It was not a fateful discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Lake Mono because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; thus, she speculated that a microbe exposed to the two substances might be able to replace each other.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is really similar to that of phosphorus."
"As a result, organisms have difficulty distinguishing these elements separately."
“But arsenic is different enough that it doesn’t work exactly like phosphorus; it penetrates inside and somehow rubbers the work of our biochemical machine,” Anbar explained.
The researchers collected the bacterium known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a life form using arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or the moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing ever showed that it could work.
Arsenic was more common at the beginning of the Earth’s existence, she says; thus, researchers have hypothesized that the first forms of life could have used it.
This suggests that there could be other ways to form life, not just the way life on Earth was formed in the beginning,” said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
The last two stolen exhibit dogs were found in Compton
The two other exhibit dogs on four burglars outside a Bellflower motel were found, Los Angeles County Sheriff's Office said on Thursday.
The four exhibit dogs — two Akitas and two Welsh Pembroke Corgis — disappeared on Tuesday when someone stole the Chevrolet Express van in which they had spent the night outside a Bellflower Motel 6, authorities said.
Two of the dogs were recovered Wednesday afternoon and the other two were found late Wednesday evening, said Steve Whitmore, a spokesperson for the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department.
“The good news is that dogs are doing well,” Whitmore said.
"They're in good shape."
"They have been returned to their legitimate owners."
Whitmore refused to say exactly where the dogs had been found, in what neighborhood and what the circumstances of their discovery were.
"An investigation is underway."
“We don’t want to say that,” Whitmore said.
“We follow the orders.”
The owners of the dogs, Kristina Rickard and David Peek, could not be joined to provide a comment Thursday.
They were gathered Wednesday afternoon with their two Akitas at a county animal shelter in Downey.
The sheriff's assistants found the van and the two dogs separately in Compton.
The Akitas - a 3-year-old male, and Didi, a 10-month-old female - were healthy and safe, authorities said.
But Bunny and Peter, the corgis Rickard and Peek had planned to show at regional competitions this week, on behalf of the owners of Japanese dogs, were missing until their discovery Wednesday evening.
Peek and Rickard, who live in Redding, are in town this weekend as part of Long Beach’s AKC/Eukanuba National Championship, where they were expected to introduce Trace.
The other dogs were expected to participate in competitions of other events scheduled in the days before the "AKC/Eukanuba" exhibition, Peek told the Times on Wednesday.
Southern California is one of the stops of the couple's nearly a month-long dog show tour.
On Monday night, Peek and Rickard checked into the motel.
They often stay in motels and park their van outside, right next to their bedroom window.
They took three other dogs – a Boxer puppy, a Parson Russell Terrier and a Breton Spaniel – who stayed with them in the motel room.
But they left the Akitas and the corgis, with thicker fur, in the van where it would be cooler.
They opened the windows a bit, so the dogs could have some fresh air.
Peek and Rickard reported the truck's theft at 6 a.m. on Tuesday.
Peek said they would offer a reward to anyone who could lead them to the corgis, equipped with an implanted microchip to identify them.
It is unclear whether a prize was awarded on Thursday.
The lion is ready to turn red again, the restructuring of MGM no longer awaits the final green light of the court
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light to start from scratch.
A federal bankruptcy judge in New York officially praised Thursday's "pre-packed" plan by creditors that about $5 billion in debt would be cleared; paving the way for the entertainment company, having 86 years of existence and broadcasting film, to focus its distribution and production efforts.
With the decision on Thursday that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. bankruptcy code, there are no longer any legal hurdles before MGM to get back under the supervision of the founders of Entertainment Spyglass, Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become a direct studio.
Staff will be reduced to approximately 320 out of 400 starting.
MGM will not actually emerge from Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase has completed a $500 million credit facility to fund MGM’s new operations and productions.
It is currently distributed under license by the investment bank, which itself is worth $75 million, and is expected to be financed by mid-December.
The process of restructuring the studio began in May 2009 when investment bank Moelis & Co. was hired to advise the management on how to place its finances since it did not have the means to pay interest of $300 million per year.
In August, the CEO, Harry Sloan, was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former CEO of Enron and a rectification expert known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper’s attempts to solve MGM’s financial difficulties and satisfy the studio’s more than 140 creditors took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, the parties agreed, at the end of 2009, to put the company up for sale.
However, the auction attracted few bidders, none of whom were willing to pay the additional $2 billion that the creditors were looking for.
In the spring of this year, everything had to be reworked as the MGM team started working on a restructuring plan that, after months of internal disagreements and debates, was finally approved by the creditors at the end of October.
When MGM officially leaves bankruptcy in the coming weeks, Moelis and Cooper receive multi-million-dollar rewards for their work.
Moelis & Co., which has already earned $1.2 million, will receive a payment of $9.5 million.
Cooper's companies, which raised $375,000 a month for their management services, will receive a "success bonus" of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum are planning to relaunch production of MGM, which has released only one film this year, and set up an annual list of seven or eight films to be released from 2012.
They also intend to co-finance two films based on "The Hobbit", with Warner Bros.
The studio must make a separate loan between $265.000.000 and $275 million to finance its share in these two films, which must be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who holds about 18% of MGM’s debt, attempted to merge the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, where he is the main shareholder.
However, the recent discussions between the two companies did not lead to an agreement.
Tech Toys to Keep Your Budget Gifts in Balance
Although the main candidate for this year’s most wonderful toy is IPAD, followed, perhaps, by Microsoft’s video game system, Kinect, both can make a major break in your gift budget.
Consider that, for the price of an iPad, you can buy five BMX bikes for $99 and a Kinect game costs the same price as 10 classic beads jumping ropes, or about 48 Play-Doh boxes.
But there are ways to keep your gift budget in balance.
Recently, I visited three national toy sellers - Wal-Mart, Toys "R" Us and BJ's Wholesale Club - to see the electronic toys I could buy for less than $80.
It’s clear that Moore’s Law has evolved, this year’s tech toy is likely to have more strength; while costing the same price, if not a little less, compared to last year.
In addition, while there are generally fewer new toys associated with websites, two of the best known of this type, Webkinz and Club Penguin, have more offers.
And button battery toys are on the rise, as well as rechargeable battery toys.
Here are some recommendations.
(All prices are from Toys "R" Us, unless otherwise indicated.)
The Sing-a-ma-jigs (Mattel, $13 for 3 years and older) are plumber-sized toys the size of an Indian pig that sing a note when you squeeze them on the belly.
One pressure is equal to one note, and a second makes it possible to compose a song.
If you buy several of them, they will sing in harmony.
Attention: once you start pushing, you can no longer stop.
To combine singing with dancing, Dance Mickey Star (Fisher-Price, $60 for 2 years and older) is the best choice.
Inspired by last year’s Elmo Live technology, the 14-inch animatronic doll plays turn-based role-playing games like Simon Says and can do lunar dance thanks to its innovative articulated feet with wheel locking.
The children who have tried the toy use Mickey as a dance instructor while their parents complain about a lack of volume control.
If you are a child of the 80s, you will remember Alphie, one of the first computerized educational toys.
It’s back (Hasbro/Playskool, $40 for 3 years and more), with a backpack filled with questionable playing cards designed to turn a ride into a session with a self-correction and a valve booklet.
If you are distrustful when your child holds your smartphone, here are three standalone alternatives.
The VTech Mobigo ($60, for 3 to 8-year-olds) is the cheapest and easiest to use, with a qwerty keyboard, although the games don’t educate as effectively as the Explorer Leapster ($70, for 3 to 12-year-olds), it’s the first major revision of the Leapster range and more reminiscent, with a screen.
No version is compatible with the old cartridges.
The iXL from Fisher-Price ($90, for 3-7 year olds) uses an iTunes-type system to offer games and ebooks and features an SD card input that allows you to view family photos.
Finally, Scrabble Flash ($30, Hasbro, for 8 years and older) is a set of five blocks barely larger than a light box, each with its own LED display.
The goal is to form words by placing the blocks online before time runs out, it is ideal for an impromptu spelling contest.
