Prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign
Prosecutors at the Department of Justice have lifted the criminal charges brought against Senator John Ensign, stemming from a case related to a former campaign assistant and his efforts to get a lobbying job for the woman's husband, the senator's lawyers announced on Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat faced by Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican candidate in the 2012 presidential election until the scandal around his case made headlines last year and damaged his career.
Mr. Ensign’s office said he was “very happy” with the decision, the result of a one-year investigation.
The senator could still be exposed to disciplinary measures taken by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign’s lawyers said the Justice Department had “informed that Senator Ensign was no longer the subject of the investigation and that he had no intention of maintaining any charges against him in this case.”
The Ministry of Justice abstained from commenting on the matter.
The announcement came as a sort of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, according to which there is significant evidence that Mr. Ensign has conspired to violate a federal criminal prohibition on lobbying.
Interviews, emails, and other documents, first reported in the New York Times in October 2009, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, get a lucrative lobbying job with her husband to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife Cyn.
Ms. Hampton once served as a treasurer during an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; according to documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been an employee of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited by law from lobbying with his former employer or the Senate as a whole for a year.
Ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, seems to contradict the so-called ban on lobbying.
According to the evidence that was made public, “there appears to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate and substantial violation of the law of the revolving door,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients from a government investigation.
Although the judge of the department refused to explain the reasoning leading to the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other lawyers in ethics said that the department appeared to be disrespectful of political prosecutions after a number of reversals followed by the decision of the high-level indictment of Steve.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the general director of Citizen Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defense group that received several complaints against Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign’s principal attorney, said in an interview that he had received a phone call from a prosecutor at the Department of Justice and follow-up the next day, telling him that the department was not seeking charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign’s team of lawyers had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed in a statement Wednesday, “had acted in accordance with the law.”
Mr. Coggins declined to specify the legal arguments he had made to the prosecution.
“I’m not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice, except to say that we think they’ve made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to drop an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that Mr. Ensign’s $96,000 payment to the Hamptons violated federal electoral law.
The Electoral Commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major Nevada company that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying jobs.
