Mr. Ensign also attended a lunch with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and asked the Secretary of Transportation to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after hiring Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When news of the case surfaced last year, Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his fourth-ranking Republican leadership position in the Senate.
After maintaining a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign said two weeks ago that he intended to run for a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesperson, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and end its investigation.
Senator Ensign is looking forward to continuing his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she says.
