Is it possible for civilization to close the gaps?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civilisation erupted in Washington this week.
Is this a precursor to true bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the quick return to the partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and Congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the major issues to be addressed during the “boxy duck” session.
But obviously, there has been at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each camp wanted to score points.
The President’s deficit committee’s public meeting on Wednesday was equally civilized, despite the political divergences that remain between members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap; but which, however, still divides the members.
This is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two sides are now in a period of trial and trial with a view to obtaining signs of cooperation and compromise, while attempting to assess the limits of public opinion and voters' patience for a renewed partisan war.
That's why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent comments from the participants revealed a minimum of requirements or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it is taxation, expenses, health care or rights, both parties remain miles away.
However, the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed on the tone,” said Pete Wehner, an official with the Bush administration, now alongside the Ethical and Public Policy Center.
“It’s inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions, and then they fade away.
That's good."
On some issues, including those on the agenda of the "boxy duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire by the end of the year, and no one is in favor of it.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of them, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is conceivable on the extension of unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, more optimism is being expressed about a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the "boxy duck", with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warns that successful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the “lame duck” session will not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is probable, if not inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done will be, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations,” he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civilization would lead to true co-operation.
"I consider most of what's going on between today and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the constituents present at the tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to keep up with their promises of cutting public spending and repealing the new Health Care Act.
These partisan positions are already clear in the early responses to the deficit committee's recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and increasing certain taxes, pushing back the retirement age and reducing spending.
Co-chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, according to themselves, imposed the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have had a hard time reaching that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the group's elected members, suggesting that there are, at least today, few motives or willingness to compromise on tax issues.
Galston envisaged two phases in the fighting between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama in terms of budget, taxes and health care; then be followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
The public opinion.
It is widely proven that, despite the supportive spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as in 1995, then the two parties will closely observe the reaction of the public.
The one who will be judged as a loser will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would still be an optimistic viewpoint.
The partisan spirit and polarization are larger today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was then between President Bill Clinton and Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a simple prelude to a more consistent election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on the part of both sides to find a common ground on the issues that still divide them.
