Warning to pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the Future Generations Association (ex- Movement for the Rights and Respect of Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have significant statistical value in relation to the low number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem dealt with", bought between July and September the foods generally consumed in four meals and one snack in a day by a child of a dozen.
These types of meals, including official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - as well as treats, have been examined by laboratories looking for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The scale of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five classified as certain carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that may act as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies from several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
“Although, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, our investigation clearly shows that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is of concern,” the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogen residues and three proven as certain carcinogens as well as nearly twenty residues that may disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack by the study, has traces of six chemical substances, but a fungicide is banned in France.
The same goes for the green beans of Kenya, included in the lunch, on which the study detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, chopped steak, boxed tuna, and even breadstick and chewing gum were stuffed with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, salmon steak was the most "rich" with 34 chemical residues detected and even examining the plastic plate used to heat the meal in the microwave was not exempt.
The final risk for the consumer of these "contaminant cocktails" is probably underestimated, according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, proposed "in the face of the urgency of the situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the increase of civilisation diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
